Ques: Which SOLID Principle follow ?

1. Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP) ✅
    The client depends on the abstraction:
    Dish dish = DishFactory.createDish("PIZZA");

    instead of:
    Pizza pizza = new Pizza();

    The client works with Dish, not concrete implementations.
    So DIP is partially followed.

2. Open/Closed Principle (OCP) ❌

    Suppose we add:
    class Burger implements Dish
    We must modify the factory:

    case "BURGER":
        return new Burger();

    Existing code changes.
    OCP says: Software entities should be open for extension but closed for modification.

    This factory is not closed for modification.
    Therefore OCP is violated.

3. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) ✅
    The factory has one responsibility:
    Create Dish objects
    So SRP is generally followed.

4. Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) ✅
    Every implementation:

    Pizza implements Dish
    Sushi implements Dish

    can be used wherever a Dish is expected:

    Dish dish = new Pizza();
    Dish dish = new Sushi();

    LSP is followed.

5. Interface Segregation Principle (ISP) ✅

    The interface is small:
    interface Dish {
        void prepare();
        void serve();
    }

    Implementations aren't forced to implement unused methods.
    ISP is followed.

Q: Which SOLID principles are followed by the switch-based Factory Pattern?
Answer:
✅ SRP – Factory is responsible only for object creation.
✅ DIP – Client depends on Dish abstraction rather than concrete classes.
✅ LSP – Any Dish implementation can replace another.
✅ ISP – Small focused interface.
❌ OCP – Violated because every new dish requires modifying the switch statement in the factory.


